course.name: How to Task on Oxygen Cocktail
course.title: How to Task on Oxygen Cocktail
course.description: This course will teach you the ins and outs of tasking on the Oxygen Cocktail project. You will learn how to complete a task, write a good hint, and accurately annotate the correctness of model responses.

contents.body: **Project Overview** Welcome to Oxygen Cocktail, a unique project that involves solving a challenging reasoning problem and creating hints to guide a model to solve the problem on its own. The idea is to gently nudge the model in the right direction without being too prescriptive, in order to see if the model can get to the right answer with the right guidance. **The overall** **aim of the project is to create a hint that corrects a model’s previous failure once within three tries.** ***Note: Pay close attention to the content in this course, as there will be an assessment at the end.***

**Project Resources** You’ll need to remember this course content while tasking, so make sure you save these project resources in a place that’s easy to refer to. * [Project Instructions](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vRqZrpEcMfBIC-HtluxMdEbcvbNyreZHaaEhMxwhTfxCM88efO1Ihw_06kISq_84KrIK-D6xttDNZEv/pub) * [Examples of Tasks with Good Hints](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1JQyfDNQhuiWBlA2X51VTXv8VIT22c2j2CbKpmx4qjEo/edit?gid=2078812755#gid=2078812755) * [Common Errors](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vT2j0Wr-n3ON9SRDypdszbDmirc06lc7ELNuc4oBjIKw6aILOzKORsjQOUrTi3eQJqwAmbDIZCosC1S/pub)

**Task Attempt Overview** Follow the 3 steps below to understand how to complete an Oxygen Cocktail task: **Step 1:** **Check that the Prompt Stumps the Model** * **Task Components**: Every task will provide you with the following components: * Prompt * Image * Incorrect Model Response * Correct Answer (GTFA) * **Expertise Check**: Check if you are able to solve the task on your own. * If you are not able to solve the prompt on your own, you should skip the task until you find one that you’re able to solve. * **Defective Task Check**: Double check the model response and make sure that its answer is incorrect. * If the Model Response matches the Correct Answer, this means the response was not incorrect and the task is defective. * Collect the Task ID, skip the task, and report it to your assigned QM. **Step 2:** **Write a Hint** * **Example Hint**: After the initial model response is generated, the model will generate an example hint. **DO NOT COPY THIS HINT** but use it as potential inspiration for the solution. * Example hints will show up as Hint 1, Hint 2, Hint 3. Do not copy this format when you write your hint. * The project prevents you from using the word Hint in your hint. * **Write your Hint**: Write a new hint that is different from the inspiration hint that will show the model how to get on the right track. * Your hint should have enough guidance to direct the model on the right thinking path, **but should not  spell out the right answer**. * Think of this as tutoring someone - you want to provide a hint that gets them on the right track without giving them the answer so they can learn on their own. * **Submit the Hint**: Submit your Hint to generate three model responses. **Step 3: Rate the 3 Hinted Model Responses** * **Model Ratings**: Answer the question, “Did the the stepwise hint make the model reach the right answer?”. Compare the model’s answer with the provided Correct Answer in the task. * If the model reaches the correct answer, mark YES. * If the model’s final answer is still wrong, mark NO.  * **One Correct Response**: At least 1 out of 3 model responses must be correct for you to submit your task * If NO model responses are correct, you need to edit your hint, and re-run the three models * If you cannot write a hint that results in at least one correct model response, then you need to skip the task.

sections.title: Step 1: Check that the Prompt Stumps the Model

contents.body: ## ***Step 1: Check that the Prompt Stumps the Model*** You will be provided a pre-loaded prompt and image pair that should be able to stump the model. 1. Submit the prompt and image by clicking **NEXT** to generate the model response. 2. Review and evaluate the problem. If you are not able to solve it, you should **SKIP** the task until you find one that you’re able to solve. **Example Prompt and Image Pair** 3. Evaluate the model response to verify that it was **stumped**. * Check the provided correct answer (GTFA) to compare against the model response. If they are different, the model is likely incorrect. 4. In the case that the model was not stumped, collect the Task ID, SKIP the task, and report the task to your assigned QM. **Example Model Response** **Provided GTFA (Correct Answer)** Note here that the model concludes the final answer should be **S**, but the confirmed correct answer is **R**. This means that the model was stumped and the task is valid to move forward with.

## ***Example Hints*** After determining that the prompt stumped the model, you will click on NEXT to generate the example hints that you can use as inspiration to write your own hint. * Do not copy this example, but use it as inspiration for your own work.  * In particular, do not copy the “Hint 1…Hint 2…Hint 3” format. The task prevents you from using the word Hint in your hint. **Example Hints** ****

## ***Write your Hint*** Write a new hint that is different from the inspiration hints to guide the model to the right approach and thought process to achieve the right result. * The hint should be general guidelines or suggested approaches to solving the problem. * Any factual errors, contradictions or miscalculations in the hint that misguide the model will result in the task’s failure. Proofread your hint for any of these mistakes before submitting. * Your hint must make the model succeed in arriving at the correct answer in at least one out of three tries. **Example Hint Writing**

## ***Additional Hint Guidelines*** * Don’t over-describe the image in your hint. Part of the goal here is for the model to use reasoning on the image. * The hint should be 100% factually accurate. If there are any factual or mathematical errors, the task will fail. * Do not address the model as “You” or use phrases like, “you are right to consider x, but you got y wrong”. * Avoid Writing Nudges: We need the hint to be a stepwise guide to solving the problem, not a **nudge**. Your hint should always be multiple sequential steps. * A nudge is a single sentence that points out a particular thing the model did wrong in order to correct it. * Do not copy the “Hint 1…Hint 2…Hint 3” format from the example hints. * See [Good & Bad Hint Examples](https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vR10Fx36ZqSqnAsm9TEWsx7eBJSurULu-w4vtfU2HXcTn657veaqK1nMO6bZPv6ZKUORBjnQMNn2kZ7/pub) for more guidance on acceptable hints on this project * Use [Appropriate LaTeX Formatting](https://www.overleaf.com/latex/templates/a-quick-guide-to-latex/fghqpfgnxggz.pdf) when writing your hints. * The hint should be written in natural language (including formulas if really needed) as if you were writing a stepwise guide to solving the problem for a student.

sections.title: Step 3: Rate the 3 Hinted Model Responses

contents.body: ## ***Step 3: Rate the 3 Hinted Model Responses*** Submit the hint and wait for the new model responses to appear. There will be 3 model responses in total and each will be generated and rated separately. This can take some time. **Example Hinted Model Response** 1. **Evaluate the model’s responses and determine if its final answer is correct** * If the final answer is correct (matches the GTFA given at the start of the task) then answer YES to the field below. * If the final answer is incorrect (it differs factually from given GTFA), mark the following field as NO. 2. **Check that at least 1 Model Response is Correct** * If none of the model responses are correct, you can edit your hint, regenerate the models, and try again. * If you can confirm that at least 1 out of 3 responses are correct, then you can submit the task. ---

## Reviewer Instructions This section is intended to guide reviewers in grading tasks and showing attempters how their tasks will be graded. **Numerical Ratings:** * **4-5 (Pass)** : Task contains no failing issues and few minor quality issues (grammar, punctuation, phrasing, clarity in hints). * **3 (Pass)** : Task contains notable minor quality issues, like grammar, punctuation, phrasing, or clarity issues in its hint, but the hint is overall accurate and useful. None of the fail conditions from the grading instructions given below are present. * **1-2 (Fail)** : Task contains at least one fail condition from the list below: 1. Any of the 3 hinted model responses are rated inaccurately. * YES is selected when the model was stumped * NO is selected when the model achieved the correct GTFA 2. All 3 model responses were still stumped even with the help of the hint * This means the hint was not helpful and the attempter did not properly check this requirement. 3. The attempter’s hint contains factual inaccuracies, contradictions, or reasoning issues * This is the most in-depth part of the review, so spend most of your time here carefully evaluating the correctness of the hint in its entirety, including approaches, formulas, and statements. 4. The attempter’s hint is not substantially different from the inspiration hints or copies all or major sections of these hints. 5. The attempter’s hint does not contain the correct answer (GTFA) to the prompt. **When to Fix the Task** * Generally try to fix any errors you come across in the hints or labels, and re-run the model if needed. * Edit the hints if they contain “Hint 1”, “Hint 2” to remove these labels and re-run the model. * Edit any statements in the hint that are objectively incorrect to correct them and re-run the model responses/re-label them. **When to SBQ the Task** * If you were unable to fix the task, select "reject this task and send it back" for another contributor to work on.

This section will show you the good and bad version of some hint examples and explain why the bad hints are bad while showing how the good hints improve on these mistakes. **Prompt - Physics:** > Wind is blowing with a speed of 20 m/s towards the south. Alice and Bob are moving along a straight path. Alice is walking south at a speed of 10 m/s, and Bob is walking north at a speed of 5 m/s. Alice is playing a flute that emits a sound at a frequency of 1000 Hz. Calculate the frequency heard by Bob. The speed of sound in still air is 340 m/s **Bad Hint:** **Why is the Hint bad?** 1. **Unclear Application of the Formula:** * A good hint should explicitly state how to apply a formula, including whether to add or subtract terms. * In this case, the hint provides the Doppler effect formula but does not specify whether to add or subtract for vo and vs. While the values and signs for vo and vs​ were given, not clarifying the correct operation within the formula can cause confusion. 2. **Lack of Clear Instructions and Proper Setup:** * A good hint should provide clear guidance on how to use the given values and formulas, including setting up the correct frame of reference and defining key positional details. * In this task, the hint fails to instruct the solver to shift to the wind/air-frame (e.g. both Alice and Bob are moving north relative to the air frame). Additionally, it does not specify whether Alice is north or south of Bob, which is crucial for determining the correct velocity signs. **Revised/Good Hint**

Here’s another example of a bad hint and its improvement. **Prompt - Math:** > A factory produces light bulbs, and the lifespan of the bulbs follows a normal distribution with a mean of 765 hours and a standard deviation of 269 hours. The company wants to package these bulbs into two different options: > > Option 1: Each bulb is sold at a fixed price of $20. > > Option 2: A premium is offered where each bulb costs 25 dollars if its lifespan is more than 900 hours and the remaining bulbs are sold at a discount 15 dollars. > > The quality control team is tasked with estimating the number of bulbs in a large shipment (500 bulbs) that will have a lifespan longer than 900 hours. After that, they will calculate the potential total revenue if all such bulbs were sold at the premium rate and the remaining are sold at the discounted rate. > > After estimating the number of bulbs with a lifespan longer than 900 hours using the properties of normal distribution and calculating the potential revenue for Option 2, determine how much more revenue the better option will provide. **Bad Hint:** **Why is the hint bad?** 1. **LaTex Formatting Issues/LaTex Missing:** * A good hint should clearly use proper formatting to display mathematical formulas and symbols like μ for mean, σ for standard deviation, and dollar signs. * In this hint, the mathematical equations and symbols (e.g., Z = (X-M)/SD, P(X>900)) are not formatted in LaTeX, making them harder to read and follow, causing readability issues and rendering issues with the dollar signs in the problem. 2. **Final Answer Included:** * A good hint should provide the necessary steps and guidance without directly giving the final answer. * In this hint, it mentions that the final answer should be $960, which can influence the thinking process and take away the challenge of working through the problem independently. A good hint should help the model reach that conclusion, not give it outright. **Revised/Good Hint**

In General, Avoid Doing Image Analysis for The Model (see example below) * More Information on this can be found on [**These Slides**](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1ETBs5zqQoCXfpatc1Y13hPDbEyroyEKqZAbXcqXulSk/edit?usp=sharing) * Telling the model exact facts about the image that it would otherwise need to interpret prevents the model from learning how to view images on its own. In the example below, the hint counts cycles for the model * An improved hint would be: > "count the number of cycle over the given interval by counting the number of peaks+troughs on the interval divided by 2"

## **Common Errors** **Common Error #1: Hints with Errors** Many hints contained factual inaccuracies, often failing to guide the model correctly. For example: * Misleading or wrong calculations (e.g., incorrect assumptions in Menelaus' Theorem or linear programming). * Errors in intermediate steps that oversimplified or skipped critical reasoning. * Poorly aligned hints with the given prompt. **✅ What You Should Do:** * **Fact-check** all formulas, theorems, and intermediate steps to ensure correctness. * **Avoid oversimplification**: Provide clear reasoning for each step. * **Align hints with the prompt**, ensuring they are specific and relevant. * **Test the hint** by working through the problem yourself. * **Clarify assumptions** when necessary to prevent confusion. **Common Error #2: Hint Depth and Nuance Issues** Hints frequently failed to provide meaningful guidance. They were either too verbose or missed critical problem-solving steps, leaving the model ill-equipped to reach the correct answer. **✅ What You Should Do:** * **Use Natural Language**: Write the hint as if you are a professor guiding a student. * **Be Clear and Precise**: Ensure the hint is understandable to someone with a solid mathematical background. * **Provide a Step-by-Step Strategy**: Outline a clear plan to solve the problem. * **Mention Relevant Theorems**: If a theorem is necessary, explicitly state it. * **Include Necessary Equations/Identities**: If an equation or formula is required, mention it explicitly. * **Keep It Focused on Problem-Solving**: The hint should help the solver develop a structured approach. ❌**What You Should NOT Do:** * **Be Vague**: Avoid hints that are too general or unhelpful. * **Give the Full Solution**: The hint should guide, not solve the problem entirely. * **Assume Prior Knowledge of the Problem**: Assume the solver hasn’t seen the problem before. * **Omit Key Steps**: Do not skip important parts of the problem-solving process. * **Use Unnecessary Jargon**: Keep the explanation clear and accessible. * **Overcomplicate the Explanation**: Keep the hint concise and to the point. **Common Error #3: LaTeX and Formatting Errors** Hints often suffered from readability problems due to poor grammar, spelling, or LaTeX formatting errors. This made interpretation difficult for reviewers. **✅ What You Should Do:** * Proofread content for errors. * **Test LaTeX formatting:** There is a LaTeX Preview below each text box to show you if your formatting renders correctly! * Structure hints clearly for easy readability. * Review this [LaTeX Guide](https://www.overleaf.com/latex/templates/a-quick-guide-to-latex/fghqpfgnxggz.pdf) (if needed) \ **Common Error #4: Plagiarism / Chatbot Usage** A significant number of hints and responses appeared to be copied directly from chatbot outputs, often without adequate revision. Key issues include broken LaTeX formatting, generic or verbose responses that lacked clarity or depth, and use of chatbot-like phrasing and structures (e.g., "Step 1," "Step 2"). | ‼**️** Do not rely on chatbots for your responses. We can easily detect unoriginal content. If found, you will be disabled and will no longer be able to task on this project. **Ensure all your responses are your own and thoroughly revised.** | | --- |
**Assessment Time** In the next section, you will be answering questions based on the content on the course, so we hope you’ve been paying attention! Good luck!

contents.question: What Is The Minimum Number of Model Responses That Must Be Correct In Order to Submit a Task on Oxygen Cocktail

choices.answer: 2 model responses out of 3 must be correct after the model uses your hint to solve the problem
3 model responses out of 3 must be correct after the model uses your hint to solve the problem
1 model response out of 3 must be correct after the model uses your hint to solve the problem
No model responses need to be correct in order to submit a task on oxygen cocktail.
A prompt
An image
A correct answer to the prompt
An initial response to the prompt, with an incorrect answer
An example hint to inspire your hint writing.

contents.question: What are the task elements that you will read and review before writing a hint? Think about everything you would expect to see before writing your hint. (SELECT ALL THAT APPLY)
Which of the following are acceptable labels for the steps in your hint? (select all that apply)

choices.answer: “Step 1.”…”Step 2”…”Step 3”…
“Hint 1”…”Hint 2”…”Hint 3”…
“First”…”Next”… “After that,”…

contents.question: What Should be the format of your hint?

choices.answer: A single sentence pointing out an error in the model’s reasoning, and how to correct it.
A stepwise guide to solving the problem in the prompt, without giving away the final answer.
A conversational guide that includes phrases like “You got this incorrect. You need to do this instead,” or “You then move on to the next step, which is…”
An exact solution to the given prompt, including all math solved and the correct answer to the problem stated.

contents.question: Which of the following is an acceptable use of the inspiration hint provided to you with your task?

choices.answer: Copying the sections that are written correctly into your own hint, while modifying the incorrect parts.
Copying the entire inspiration hint exactly for your first hint
Copying a few sentences from the inspiration hint, but mostly writing your first hint in your own words.
Following the same format as the inspiration hint (for instance, stepwise formatting, as long as you don’t copy “Hint 1”, “Hint 2”, etc) but writing your hint entirely in your own words.

contents.question: Which of the following mistakes will cause a task to fail on Oxygen Cocktail? (select all correct answers)

choices.answer: Writing a hint identical to the inspiration hint
Having any mathematical or factual errors in your hint
Including the GTFA in your hint
Copying text from the inspiration hint

contents.question: What is wrong with the following hint excerpt? Assume these are the last two lines of the hint (you do not need math knowledge to get this right, or the remainder of the task) **Statement:** For example, for point A, the x-value on the graph is 1.2, the y-value is 1.4, and the corresponding value on the regression line is \(2x = 2.4\) Plug \\( x_n \\) and \\(\\bar{x}\_n\\) into the formulas for all four values, and then take the difference between the two formula outputs.

choices.answer: The hint statement uses unnecessary jargon in describing the math being performed
The hint statement is too vague in its mathematical phrasing
The hint statement contains the exact GTFA to the prompt
The statement over-explains the image by finding coordinate values the model should have determined on its own
